AGI - White snus has long-term effects on oral health, with painful inflammations> that can last months or up to a year. It reveals a research led by the University of Gothenburg, published in Journal of Oral Medicine. Snus is a Swedish term used to indicate wet tobacco powder for oral use, produced through a process of steam humidification. In Italy and throughout the European Union the sale and distribution of snus is prohibited since 1992, according to the directive on tobacco products (2014/40/EU).
&nbsp;
But it is still possible to buy it in Sweden, the country of origin, and to import it for personal use. White snus, a form of oral tobacco without tobacco, became popular among young people as an alternative to traditional snus. Researchers at the University of Gothenburg noted that injuries associated with white snus are different from traditional snus and require immediate attention.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The widespread use of white snus among young people raises significant concerns about long-term oral health. Recent clinical observations have revealed that it can cause painful and persistent inflammations in the mouth, other than those associated with brown snus.
&nbsp;
For research about 40 patients were recruited with oral mucosa lesions associated with the use of white snus. The tissue samples have been examined to assess the severity of inflammation and changes in tissues. The results were compared with those of brown snus users and a control group of non-users. The results showed that injuries associated with white snus are characterized by redness and thinning of the mucosa, with a severe inflammation that can last months or up to a year.
&nbsp;
This is significantly different from injuries associated with brown snus, which tend to heal within a few weeks. The widespread use of white snus among young people, especially among women, raises significant concerns about long-term oral health. The lack of knowledge about the long-term consequences of using white snus requires continuous monitoring and further research.
&nbsp;
The study highlights the need for greater awareness of the potentially harmful effects of white snus on oral health. The results suggest that users should be advised to stop using snus immediately if they notice problems or alterations. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
